AGI – Traffic in tilt, deviated roads and security men ready to help lost visitors and residents in the unusual hustle and bustle of Lower Manhattan, a neighborhood famous for its proximity to the Financial District of the Big Apple and to accommodate Battery Park, > considered one of the most beautiful parks in the metropolis (after Central Park) for its strategic position, on the southern tip of the island, overlooking the sea: a privileged spot to enjoy a spectacular view of the Statue of Liberty.
&nbsp;
But this morning to be crowded more so was the corner of Battery Park where the statue of Giovanni da Verrazzano> stands majestic: its largest bronze bust, shaped in the early 1900s by the sculptor Ettore Ximenes and placed on an elaborate granite pedestal with lateral turns. On the façade there is the sculpture of a female figure, allegory of discovery and exploration: the two life goals for Giovanni Da Verrazzano, a Florentine navigator who first, on April 17, 500 years ago, sailed with his ship the Bay of New York by sighting Staten Island, Brooklyn and Manhattan> before continuing along other lands on the Atlantic Ocean, up to Maine.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The statue was dedicated to him in 1921 but today, at his feet, the highest Italian institutions, New York and the Tuscany Region. With the Governor of the State of New York, Kathy Hochul> and the Mayor of the metropolis, Eric Adams>, participated in the celebrations, among others, the Vice-President of the House Giorgio Mulé> (FI), the Consuls &nbsp; of Italy and of France in New York, Fabrizio di Michele and Cedrik Fouriscot, Susan Donoghue>, commissioner of the parks of New York, Massimozzi
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
A partor that New York devotes only to great events. In this case, the memorable anniversary of a great character: the Florentine navigator and explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano that, exactly 500 years ago, on board the sailor Dauphine, flying French flag crossed – the first European of history – the seas of the Bay of New York.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; To remember the courageous enterprise were also responsible for the main Italian American organizations – the National Italian American Foundation (NIAF) and the Italian American Leadership Forum (IALF) - who actively collaborated on the round of commemorative events that will hold the counter in today and tomorrow. &nbsp; Because the five hundredth anniversary of Verrazzano, they emphasized the interventions, offers to the Italian-Americans and to those who know the history of the famous explorer, "a great opportunity to remember so much the event, so much the 'Spirito della Scoperta' and its importance".
&nbsp; From the same point of view the Vice-President of the Camera Mullé who, answering the AGI, has evidenced how Da Verrazzano is first and foremost a great humanist and a great Italian: “a character – he said – has nothing to envy to Christopher Columbus, Caboto or Vespucci.”
&nbsp;
It is true, in his opinion, the emphasis that today is given to this anniversary because "at a distance of 5 centuries - Mulé continued - we still remember how his enterprise managed to connect concretely two worlds, Europe and America, and to change the history of humanity opening the doors of the world to the largest laboratory of civilizations, to which Italians and Italian Americans continue to give fundamental contributions".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp; In New York, with the Vice-President of the Chamber, there are several representatives of Italian Regions and Cities who were on their way overseas: in addition to the President of the Tuscany Region Eugenio Giani, will attend the commemorative events, today and tomorrow, the governor of Friuli Venezia Giulia (region guest of honor of the Gala 2024 of the Niaf) Massimiliano Fedriga and the Mayor of Palermo, Roberto Lagalla, in New York to promote the new air connection directed with the island but especially the 400 years of the Patroness of Palermo, Santa Rosalia, equally venerated in the Big Apple. (AGI)
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

