AGI -&nbsp;A parade of dromedaries, camels, lamas and alpaca on the agenda for Saturday under the Eiffel Tower is the subject of heated controversy by the environmentalists, who at the moment got the momentary suspension of the unusual event. The controversial event is organized by the French Federation for the development of camelids in France and Europe. It is part of the International Year of Camelliads, proclaimed by the UN to promote "the essential contribution" of these "heroes of deserts and highlands" that support "millions of families living in hostile environments in more than 90 countries".
<br> According to the Parisian fashion show organizer, the mayor of Janvry (Essone) Christian Schoettl, is a way to support "the cause of camel in the French capital of human rights". Since 2019 Janvry, a locality in Paris, has hosted two international camel shows. Schoettl reported that he was "in love" of these animals at first sight and possessing four dromedaries that he carries "on holiday".
&nbsp;
For this Parisian parade, he claims to have mobilized 70 thousand euros of funding, 34 national delegations, 80 people to supervise the event, including three veterinarians, an ambulance of civil security, two vans to rescue animals if necessary and persons in the collection of waste. However, his arguments did not convince the animal protection association 'Paris Animaux Zoopolis', which denounced the use of camels, dromedaries, lamas and alpaca as "empty entertainment" and "volgarious food resources".
&nbsp;
"These animals are adapted to the desert, to the high temperatures and drought. They have no place in Paris," argued Amandine Sanvisens, <br> co-founder of the association.
&nbsp;
The city of Paris "is not favourable to this parade" but has no decision-making power, "because the event is traveling", according to sources of the Hotel de Ville. The event should take place on Saturday afternoon between the Quai de Seine, opposite the Eiffel Tower, Les Invalides and the UNESCO headquarters, all in the 7th arrondissement of the Capital. The final decision to authorise or not the event is for the Police Prefecture, which has not officially pronounced itself.&nbsp;

